Perspectives on Sino-American Relations in 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, a new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of Sino-American relations unsettled wide parts of Asia.
Last year, US President Donald Trump returned from his particularly pompous "State Visit Plus" in Beijing, which China had hoped would finally put an end to Trump's anti-Chinese election campaign rhetoric afterwards.
Twelve months later, China and the United States are embroiled in a trade war, and the Trump government has replaced the "strategic engagement" of the US in China with "strategic competition".
In addition, the US, European, and Chinese economies and markets were booming a year ago.
There is great uncertainty prevailing on financial markets today, with growth slowing in China and Europe, and higher interest rates beginning to take effect in America.
The uncertainty over the future development of nuclear talks with North Korea also casts a shadow.
What are the prospects for the relationships between the US and China in 2019, then?
It is likely that there will be an agreement by March on the dismantling of the bilateral trade deficit and on China's import decisions related to this.
An agreement on customs duty reductions is also possible by then, although the complexity of the issue could extend the planned timeframe.
If one inch were negotiated after the other, a year could slip in.
If Chinese economic reformers were to adopt a more drastic approach by gradually committing to the abolition of all tariffs and calling on Americans to follow suit, a quicker outcome could be achieved.
That would, however, go against the grain of Chinese trade officials who are trained for decades to spare nothing, let alone everything at once.
The reform of the so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively uncomplicated.
Despite this, a reform is something other than the way contractual agreements could be interpreted in practice, even if there were no specific provisions for technology transfer at all.
The protection of intellectual property is, however, extremely problematic.
Earlier agreements made under the administration of President Barack Obama could be reaffirmed.
Pursuing enforcement or taking legal action in cases of rights infringement on intellectual property, however, remains a hopeless endeavor.
A possible mechanism involves subjecting relevant contracts between Chinese and foreign companies to international arbitration tribunals seated in Singapore or Switzerland that are specifically mandated to enforce intellectual property protection.
If China were to raise objections, it could develop its own international trade arbitration procedure located in China.
For that, it would have to appoint qualified foreigners to its arbitration panel, in order to strengthen its international credibility.
No one trusts Chinese commercial courts.
China must move towards completely independent trade and civil chambers of its judiciary system for its own internal reform needs, even if the criminal chamber continues to be subject to political control.
US concerns regarding the state subsidies in the context of China's "Made in China 2025" strategy are unlikely to be resolved.
The fact is that all countries provide their domestic tech industries with a level of state support, even if this is highest in China.
Even if we would prescribe a maximum amount of state support for a particular company, compliance would be difficult to evaluate.
I'm not optimistic that there will be a negotiated outcome in this area.
Perhaps America has to simply knock China out of the running by increasing public investments in research and development in the fields of information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not rule out the possibility that China offers tariff reforms to the rest of the international community.
China could thereby decide in the course of time to agree not only with the US but with all WTO member states on duty-free trade.
In this way, China would have a nearly irresistible opportunity to position itself as a champion of global free trade and to counter the trend towards protectionism.
In the course of such a shift, China could ask the TPP member states to join, to overtake the US (which has withdrawn from the trade agreement as one of Trump's first executive actions) in the Asia-Pacific region.
China can be surprisingly nimble when it discovers a political opening and market access.
The negotiations would be difficult, but Japan's reservations about China's accession to the TPP have diminished since Prime Minister Shinzo Abe's recent visit to Beijing.
In light of the central strategic challenges in its relationship with the US, China was likely to have sought to de-escalate conflicts in its relations with other countries in 2019 in its general foreign and security policy.
In relations to Japan there is already a certain normalization.
Latest data from the Japanese Coast Guard suggest a significant decline in Chinese incursions into the area around the Senkaku/Diaoyu Islands in the East China Sea.
China also wants to ease tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations over the South China Sea by accelerating negotiations for a "code of conduct."
In addition, China is likely to have a more relaxed relationship with India after the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
And China could begin to moderate its stance towards Taiwan in light of the election defeat suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party of Taiwanese President Tsai Ing-wen, who advocates for independence, in last month's local and regional elections.
This would naturally change radically if the US continued with further significant arms sales to Taiwan, which is likely.
Incidents at sea with the United States in the South China Sea continue to occur, and the conflict could escalate if the United States further emphasizes its stance on "freedom of navigation" next year.
China will continue to implement its major project "New Silk Road" across all of Eurasia.
In recent months, however, the initiative has caused less political uproar in China.
Discussions among Chinese officials are already underway to revise certain modalities after Sri Lanka's transfer of the Hambantota port to China sparked negative reactions and raised concerns about the long-term financial sustainability of the New Silk Road.
Triumphant announcements about the New Silk Road could therefore be heard less frequently in 2019.
In addition, China is likely to solidify and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions, rather than highlighting new institutions of international political action.
He is likely to appear as a new advocate for the WHO and maintain his stance on global climate change, as agreed upon in the Paris Climate Agreement of 2015.
More measured representatives of China's foreign policy establishment believe it is better to focus on existing mechanisms of the global rule-based system, particularly when the US consistently shows contempt for it.
While China attempts to stabilize its relations with the US and reduce tensions in its relations with other countries, its leadership will likely use 2019 to form a well-informed opinion about the future of US policy: The consequences of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his administration, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would change the new US strategy in any way.
Although they have already concluded that America's stance towards China has fundamentally changed, they are still uncertain about the exact form this change will take and whether a basic strategic shift (as opposed to tactical measures) is indicated.
